{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1vuillard_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604562/1945080701/0652.xml":{"full_text":"Traffic Records Set\nBy United Airlines\nIn First Half\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nNew all-time records were estab\nlished by United Air Lines for pas\nsenger, mail and express transporta\ntion in the second quarter and first\nhalf of 1945, W. A. Patterson, presi\ndent, announced today.\nNet income for the second quarter\nwas $1,898,497, equivalent to $1.18\nper share on common and $18.22 on\npreferred. In the same period in\n1944, net income was $1,814,754. For\nthe six months ended June 30, net\nIncome was $3,541,785, equivalent to\n$2.20 per share on the common and\n$33.98 on preferred. This compares\nwith $2,924,847 in the first half of\n1944.\nNet earnings for both periods will\nbe very materially reduced, Mr. Pat\nterson said, if the company\u2019s mail\nrate is lowered from 60 cents per\nton mile to 32 cents, the figure\nnamed by the Civil Aeronautics\nBoard.\nBankers Call Outlook Bright.\nBankers all over the country re\ngard the business outlook as favor\nable, \u201cwith consumers ready to con\nsume and producers ready to pro\nduce,\u201d Wllliafh R. Kuhns, editor of\n'Banldng, has announced. Postwar\nhousing will be one of the brightest\nbusiness spots, he asserts, people\nwanting better homes of every type.\nHis views are the result of numer\nous polls and national surveys.\nFrom January through July 28\ndepartment store sales in the Fifth\nDistrict were 11 per cent ahead of\n1944.\nThe largest mutual savings in\nstitution in this territory is the\nSavings Bank of Baltimore, with\n$124,389,618 deposits.\nThe Federal Housing Administra\ntion reports insured loans aggre\ngating $8,300,000,000 under all phases\nof its operations.\nHigh Business Volume Seen.\nAmerican business is prepared to\nresume operations on a minimum\nbasis of 1939 levels within 90 days\nafter V-J day, Bache Co. an\nnounced today following a tele\ngraphic survey. In 1939 national\nincome was $70,000,000,000 as com\npared with an estimated $160,000,\n000,000 in 1945.\nThe survey indicated that most\nexecutives expect postwar volumes\nto exceed the 1939 levels, especially\nin the agricultural, industrial ma\nchinery, air conditioning, building,\nautomotive, chemical, electrical\nequipment, household appliance and\nfurnishing fields.\nThe Bankers\u2019 National Life In\nsurance Co., Montclair, N. J., today\nannounced the appointment of Isi\ndor Blem and David Clein as gen\neral agents for Washington and\nvicinity.\nEdward Hall of W. B. Hibbs Co.\nis passing a two-week vacation at\nOcean City.\nY. E. Booker, resident partner in\nAlexander Brown Sons, is taking\na vacation and is now at Ocean\nCity, Md.\nInterest in the brokerage offices\ncentered today in the new atom\nbomb and what it might do in end\ning the war and bringing the re\nconversion period closer. Opinions\nvaried greatly.\nD. C. Exchange More Active.\nTrading on the Washington Stock\nExchange opened the week with\nconsiderably more activity than in\nthe preceding week. Garfinckel\ncommon, Washington Gas issues,\nand Potomac Electric Power 5% per\ncent preferred were in good demand\nyesterday, all selling near their\nbest prices of the year. Capital\nTraction 5s again sold at 106Vi, the\nyear\u2019s top price.\nBusiness Briefs\nLiving Costs of the average fam\nily of wage earners and lower\nsalaried clerical workers in June\nrose 0.7% above the preceding month\nto the highest level since 1921, the\nIndustrial Conference Board report\ned. The June index was 106.9, a\nrise of 2.3% from a year ago and\n24.3% above January, 1941, base\nmonth for the Little Steel formula.\nEastern Gas Fuel Associates\nawarded $40,000,000 of first mortgage\nand collateral trust 3V4% bonds to\nMellon Securities Corp. on a bid of\n100.5599. Reoffering is expedted to\nmorrow.\nNew York Central Railroad\nawarded $8,800,000 of 1 Vi equip\nment trust certificates to a group\nheaded by Salomon Bros. Hutzler\non a bid of 99.019. The issue was\nreoffered at prices to yield .95% to\n1.85%.\nPure Oil Co. earned $6,600,000 or\n$1.17 a share in the half vs. $6,500,\n000 or $1.14 a year ago.\nPittston Co. net for the half was\n$925,292 or $1.33 vs. $587,313 or 75\ncents.\nCoca-Cola International Corp.\nearned $1,245,311 or $6.31 in the June\nquarter vs. $1,252,325 or $6.33 a year\nago.\nDecca Records, Inc., net for the\nhalf was $450,284 or $1.16 vs. $504,\n620 or $1.30.\nHeyden Chemical Co. earned\n$598,050 or $1.15 in the half vs. $467,\n256 or 88 cents.\nGeneral American Transportation\nCorp. profit for the half was $1,\n634,648 or $1.57 vs. $1,676,969 or $1.61\nin the first half of 1944.\nReo Motors, Inc., earned $1,353,116\nor $2.79 in the half vs. $958,443 or\n$2.06 a year ago.\nWeston Electrical Instrument Co.\nnet for the half was $244,060 or $1.52\nvs. $239,128 or $2.11 in the same 1944\nperiod.\nAbbott Laboratories earned $1/\n441,139 or $1.62 in the half vs. $1,\n412,433 or $1.59 a year ago.\nRemington Arms Co. net for the\nhalf was $1,160,000 or 14 cents vs.\n$704,000 or 8 cents in the same 1944\nperiod.\nElectric Storage Battery Co.\nearned $1,046,278 or $1.15 in the half\nvs. $1,004,747 or $1.10 a year ago.\nPillsbury Flour Mills, Inc., profit\nfor 12 months ended May 31 was\n$1,601,045 or $2.46 vs. $1,163,547 or\n$2.12 in the preceding fiscal period.\nAmerican Distilling Co. earned\n0752,844 or $3.01 in 9 months ended\nJune 30 vs. $590,03$ or $2.36 a year\nago.\nPanhandle Producing Refining\nCo. net for 6 months ended June 30\nwas $532,350 or 58 cents vs. $184,209\nor 20 cents in the first half of 1944.\nF. W. W7oolworth Co. sales for\nJuly totaled $36,159,382, a gain of\n4.3% from a year ago; for 7 months,\n$250,515,059, an increase of 5%.\nLemer Stores Corp. sales for July\ntotaled $6,985,522, a gain of 1.7%\nfrom a year ago.\nMcCrory Store Corp. sales for\nJuly totaled $5,444,621, an increase\nof 0.5% from a year ago; for seven\nmonths, $37,633,324, a gain of 4.2%\nW. T. Grant Co. sales for July\ntotaled $12,534,882, a gain of 1.8%\nfrom a year ago; for 7 months, $93,\n254.794, up 8.9% from a year ago.\nCom Products Refining Co. re\nported corn shortages will cut its\nAugust grind to 60% of normal vs.\n80% in July.\nStudebaker Co. is negotiating with\nthe Army to reopen its South Bend\nplant to make B-29 engine parts.\nSullivan Machinery Co. received a\n$3,008,600 cutback on Russian lend\nlease orders for coal machines.\nBendix Aviation Corp. announced\nformation of a new division, Bendix\nInternational, to handle its for\neign trade program.\nI N. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE\nfFurnished by the Associated Press.)\n8ales\u2014\nstock and Ada Met\nDividend Rat*. 00. Hlth Low S:SO. cb\u00abe\nA C P Brill_ 4 12% 12% 12%-%\nAdams Exp .20* 14% 14% 14%\nAir Reductn la. 16 41% 40% 40% -1\nAlaska Juneau. 8 7% 6% 6%\nAllei corn_ 48 4% 4 4%-\nAlleg Pi _ 16 48 46% 47 -1\nAlleg prior pf.. 2 61% 61% 61%\nAlleg Lud St 80c 7 30% 30 30\nAllen Ind V\u00abe 1 16 16 16\nAllied Cbem4 160 199 159 -1\nAllied Mills lg 1 29% 29% 29%-%\nAllied Strs 1.60. 19 28% 27% 27%-%\nAllls-Chal 1.60. 6 49% 45 49\nAmalg Leather 2 5% 5% 5%\nAm a! Leath pf 3 1 45% 45% 45%\nAmerada Pet 3 4 109 107% 108 -3%\nAm AgC 1.20a. 1 30% 30% 30%-%\nAm Airlines le 8 59% 98% 58% -1%\nAm Bk Note 80g 5 27 25% 25% -1%\n\u2022Am Bk N pf 8. 10 78 78 78\nAm Boscb %g 4 16% 16% 16%\nAm Brake Sh la 2 43 42% 42% -1%\nAm CableARad 23 11 10% 10%\n\u2022Am Can pf 7 110190 189 189 -1\nAm Car A F 3g_ 5 53 52% 52% -1%\nAm CarAF pf 7. 2 113 117% 112%\nAm CbaloAC 2 7 29% 29% 29%\nAm Colortp.AOc 1 19 19 19\nAmCrystSuc. 3 27 21% 21% -1\nAm DistlUerrs.. 5 35 35 35\nAm Encaustic 1 5% 5% 5%\nAm Export L 2. 8 39% 33% 33% -2%\nAmAPrnPwr. 3 4% 4% 4%\nAmFPS6pf4Vik_ 1 100% 100% 100%\nAmPFS7pfS V\u00abk. 2 106 106 106\nAmAPP 2d of 16 27 26 26% -1%\nAm Hawaii S3 2 43% 43 43 -1\nAm HldeALeath 11 8 7% 7%\nAm HomP 2.40a 1 76 76 76 -1\nAm lee ..7 8 7% 7%\nAm Ice pf 4%c.. 1 95 95 95\nAm Intern .20g. 3 9% 9% 9%\nAm Invest.60 