appeared In\nmetals, rubbers, motors and oils.\nSales tapered occasionally as the\nmarket attempted a comeback, but\nthe Idea that reconversion might be\ncloser because of the new bomb\nheld back buying orders.\nLosers included United States\nSteel, Bethlehem, Chrysler, Good\nyear, Montgomery Ward, Caterpillar\nTractor, Boeing, United Aircraft,\nAmerican Telephone, American\nSmelting, Johns-Manvllle, Santa Pe.\nSouthern Pacific, Northern Pacific,\nStandard Oil (New Jersey) and\nRadio Corp. Union Carbide and\nEastman Kodak managed to stay\nahead.\nBonds were narrow and mixed.\nWhen news of the bomb develop\nment hit yesterday. It caught Wall\nStreet off guard and stocks drifted\naimlessly.\nBut customers investigated over\nnight. They found, for instance,\nthat Vanadium Corp. of America\nproduced uranium used in the new\ncosmic weapon. Shortly after the\nopening this stock shot up almost 3\npoints from last night\u2019s close of 24.\nWashington Produce\nFrom the Department of Agriculture.\nPrices paid net fob. Washington.\nEGGS\u2014Market firm. Most of present\nsupply coming from Midwest. This sup\nplemented by small lots from nearby sec\ntions and from local storage stocks. De\nmand continues active. Prices paid for\nFederal-State graded eggs received from\ngrading stations August 7: Whites, browns,\nmixed colors, U. 8. grade A. extra large,\n53; large 61: U 8. grade A. medium. 46;\nU. S. grade B. large. 45. Light arrivals\nof commercially graded extra large A.\n52-63.\nLIVE POULTRY\u2014Market very firm. Two\nloads arrived today and one late Monday\nfor authorized processors. Processors re\nport increasing difficulty In securing poul\ntry to fill packing quotas for the armed\nforces. No live poultry for civilian use\nso far this week. Prices paid f.o.b. Wash\nington (transportation charges Included\naccording to mileage Fowl, 27.0; broil\ners and fryers, 32.20-32.30\nChicago Livestock\nCHICAGO. Aug. 7 (>P rWFA>.\u20148alable\nhogs, 6.000; total. 11.000; active and\nfully stetdv; good and choice barrows and\ngilts at 140 bounds tip at 14.76 ceiling:\ngood and choice sows at 14.00; complete\nclearance.\nSalable cattle. 7.000: total. 7,OCX): sal\nable calves, 1,000; total. 1.000; choice fed\nsteers and yearlings steady at 17.25 up\nwards; top. 18.00. the ceiling, paid for\ntwo loads, best yearlings. 17.75: heifer\nyearlings. 17.25: all other grades steers\nand heifers weak to 25 cents lower: very\nslow: bulk fed steers and yearlings, 15.00\n17.50; grassy kinds. 12.00-14 50; heifers\nmainly steady to weak; cows and bulls\nabout ateady: cutter cows, 8.25 down:\nweighty sausage bulls to 13.25: vealers\nsteady at 16.(Xl down: stock cattle very\nslow and weak.\nSalable sheep. 6,000: total, 6.000: early\nsales slaughter native spring lambs steady\nto 15 cents higher; other slaughter classes\nsteady; good and choice native spring\nlambs. 14.25-14.50; good and choice Idaho\nspringers held at 14.75-14.85; load good\nand choice shorn Washington wethers, fall\nshorn pelts, 13.00. with accompanying\nyearling ewes to breeders at 14.50; shorn\naged native ewes. 6.60 down: about 200\nI head good and choice 67-77-pound Wash\ni ington new crop feeding lambs late Mon\nI day, 15.25._\nOdd-Lot Dealings\nPHILADELPHIA. Aur. 7 OP.\u2014The Se\ncurities Commission reported today these\ntransactions by customers \u00abith odd lot\ndealers or specialists on the New York\nStock Exchange for August 6: 3.289 pur\nchases involving 95.366 shares; 2.887\nsales involving 70.089 shares. Including\n28 short sales involving 825 shares.\nChicago Grain\nCHICAGO. Aus. 7 OPI.\u2014The grain fu\nture* market today felt repercussions from\npredictions that the atomic bomb would\nehorten the war. and prices, ta the absence\nof support from other sources, sagged\nthroughout the session.\nA rallying tendency was In evidence for\na while, but with commission houses\nheavily on the selling side and scarcely\nany mill buying of wheat the opening\nbreak was largely gustalned until the close.\nRye suffered the biggest setback,\namounting to 1% cents at one time, as\ntraders reacted sympathetically to a simi\nlar recession at Winnipeg After stop loss\norders were uncovered there was some\nbuying of the September contract by\nbrokers who sometimes act for large op\nerators.\nAt the close wheat was to 1% lower.\nSeptember. 1.64%-%; torn was to\nlower. December. 1.17; oats were to\n1% lower, September. 63%-%; rye was\nto 1% lower, September. 1.45%-%:\nbarley was unchanged to lower. Sep\ntember, 1.10.\nWheat.\u2014Open High. Law. Close.\nSept._1.05% 1 65% 1.04% 1.04\u2019,-%\nDec. _1.05% 1.65% 1.04% 1.04%-%\nMay 1.04% 1.05 1.04 1.04%-%\nJuly _ 1.58% 1.58% 1.57% 1.57%\nCORN\u2014\nDec. _ 1.17% 1.17% 1.17 1.17\nMay _1.10% 1.10% 1.10% 1.16%\nJuly 1.15% 1.15% 1.15% 1.15%\nOATS\u2014\nSept._ .0.3 .03% .02% .02%-%\nDec. _ .03% .03% .62% ,03%-b3\nMay _04-03% .04% .63% .63%\nJuly .01% .01% .60% .00%\nRYE\u2014\nSept._1.45% 1.46V, 1.44% 1.45%-%\nDec. _1.40% 1.40% 1.39% 1.40%-%\nMay -1.36% 1.30% 1.35% 1.36%\nJuly 1.31% 1.32 1.31 1.31%\nBARLEY\u2014\nSept._1.10 1.10% 1.09% 1.10\nDec. -1.10 1.10% 1.09% 1.10%\nMay 1.11 1.11 1.10% 1.10%\nPlanes now link Johannesburg,\nSouth Africa, with London in 47\nhours.\nSales\u2014\n_ Stock and Add Set\nDividend Rate 00 High. Low. 2:30. chge.\nOS Plywood .80 9.30 29% 30\nUS Realty 5 2% 27* 2%\nUS Rubber 2 15 54% 537* 537* 7*\nUS Smelt R&M 2 61 60\u2018* 60% -17*\nUS S R&Mnf3V4 1 81% 81'* BIT* +1\nUS Steel 4 43 677* 66'* 667* -17*\nUS Steel ol 7 3 150 149% 1497*\nUSTobac 1.20_. 18 24 23\u2018* 237* -17*\nUnit Stkyda V\u00abe. 1 5% 5% 57*- 7*\nUtd Stores A 5 7 67* 67* 7*\nUnlv Lab 3 67* 67* 674\ntUnlvLabpf27*. 20 437* 43'* 43'*\n\u25baUnlv Leaf 4 50 87 87 87\nUnlv Pictures 2. 8 257* 247* 247* 7*\nVan Norman l _. 3 137* 137* 1374\nVanadium 7*g._ 60 277* 257* 2674 +2'*\nVerttent C S lg. 2 167* 1674 16'* 74\nVa Caro Chm 5 57* 574 574 7*\nVa-C C 6%pf 3k 2 6774 667* 66'* -17*\ntVirgin Ry *7*.. 1 487* 487* 48'* 74\nWaldorf Sy